{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512251"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11866"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.02,0.77,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4466"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman, who was previously healthy, presents to the emergency department after 3 days of fever and rigors complaining of shortness of breath. On examination, the patient is afebrile but demonstrates dyspnea and tachypnea with a pulse oximetry reading of 89%. An arterial blood gas is performed, while the patient is on room air, with the following results: PH 7.30 (7.35\u20137.45), PCO\u003Csub\u003E2 \u003C/sub\u003E55 (32\u201345)mm Hg, PO\u003Csub\u003E2 \u003C/sub\u003E70 (72\u2013104) mm Hg, HCO\u003Csub\u003E3 \u003C/sub\u003E25(22\u201330)mEq/L and SaO2 of 93%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most accurate interpretation of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary respiratory acidosis with compensation","Primary metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation","Primary metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation","Primary respiratory acidosis without compensation","Primary respiratory acidosis with partial compensation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe person is in a state of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory acidosis without compensation\u003C/strong\u003E. The pH (7.30) is below the normal range (7.35\u20137.45), thus acidosis is present. The PaCO2 is elevated, indicating respiratory acidosis. The value consistent with the pH is PaCO2. Therefore, this is a primary respiratory acidosis. The HCO3 is within the normal range and so there is a lack of compensation. Thus, the correct answer is a primary respiratory acidosis without compensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary respiratory acidosis with compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would have an elevated PaCO2 an elevated HCO3 and pH within the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would have a low HCO3 a low PaCO2 and a normal pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation \u003C/strong\u003Ewould have a low HCO3 and low PaCO2 but the PaCO2 would not be so low as to normalise the pH, therefore they would still have a low pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E primary respiratory acidosis with partial compensation\u003C/strong\u003E would have a low pH, elevated PaCO2 and elevated HCO3. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory acidosis can be acute or chronic. In acute respiratory acidosis, the PaCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E is elevated above the upper limit of the reference range (ie, \u0026gt;45 mm Hg) with an accompanying acidemia (ie, pH \u0026lt; 7.35). In chronic respiratory acidosis, the PaCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E is elevated above the upper limit of the reference range, with a normal or near-normal pH secondary to renal compensation and elevated serum bicarbonate levels (ie, \u0026gt;30 mEq/L). Acute respiratory acidosis is present when an abrupt failure of ventilation occurs. Respiratory acidosis is the result of depression of the respiratory centre due to pulmonary or neuromuscular disorders. Examples of pulmonary disorders include asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, adult respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), severe pulmonary fibrosis, pulmonary infection (severe), chest wall disease, and chest wall deformity. Examples of neuromuscular disorders are strokes, over sedation from sedatives, myasthenia gravis, motor neuron disease e.g. amyotrophic lateral sclerosis [ALS], Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome, and muscular dystrophy. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is the most common cause of respiratory acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are many causes of metabolic acidosis including diarrhoea, diabetic ketoacidosis, renal failure, lactic acidosis and some medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Uncompensated respiratory acidosis occurs when respiratory acidosis is present, with pH acidic (under 7.35) and PaCO\u2082 acidic (over 45) mmHg; but the metabolic system does not act to correct it, marked by HCO\u2083 in the normal range (22 - 26 mEq/L)."],"references":["Sood P, Paul G, Puri S. Interpretation of arterial blood gas. Indian J Crit Care Med. 2010 Apr;14(2):57-64."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T12:21:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T21:34:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4466"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro